76561198077285928,Recommended,265990,10420931,"Posted: 10 June, 2014",all,Mustardoish,"I am shocked by the amount of negative reviews.This game is challenging and unforgiving, but I would definitely not call it unfair or RNG pure. It simply has a steep learning curve and is especially punishing for new players. Once the mechanics are known, it becomes very possible to migitate the risks. 9  out of 10 times death occurs, it is the players mistake. When I started to play on server, I lost all my heritages and had to build my heritages from scratch. It didn't take me near as long to get the essentials as for my first time.Many of the challenges that seem impossible become quite likely to do.But the advantages of this title are great. The best thing about it is the lack of grinding. Compared to other Rogue-likes, for instance Dungeons of Dredmor, this game feels quick. You dont have to slash through hordes and hordes of minions until you find a boss that kills you. Instead, each encounter counts. It should keep you focused. And when you die, you dont feel bad of having invested hours upon hours.Also the way the leveling works and the infinite amount of dungeons makes it not necessary to kill every enemy to scrap as much xp as possible to slightly stay ahead of the curve. Instead, running away is often the smart thing to do. And the levelling is fast.  In one or two hours you could reach hypothetically lvl 20. Equipment is not terribly randomized, you simply have to find the right type of equipment (i.e. sword etc) and enchant it(which is random, but still works fine). This gives it an amount of predictability and you can actually plan your character nicely.And the game has an great depth. After 200+ hours I still find new things. For that price, I would call it one of the best buys I ever had on steam.Last but not least the game has great support via a website with tons of useful information and an in-game chat feature. The community is very helpful and I had some great conversations with great people.So if you don't mind a challenge and opt for a great game and social experience, pick up this title.Edit 2015: The game had a major update that made crafting possible and also added a casual mode. Both of these should made the introduction to the game a little easier. Also, I added a beginners guide to get beginners going.In addition, I played a lot of other rogue-likes and can probably pinpoint a little more, why I like this one most. It has, similar to The Binding of Isaac and Spelunky, simple mechanics and no real story. This sets it apart from say Nethack or Tales of Maj-Eyal, which are great games by the way, but you have quite difficult mechanics and especially in the case of TOME, huge amount of statistics and finetuning. In Rogue's tale, you have only few stats and they are not finely graded, so that you have to spend too much time compromising (which always feels a bit unsatisfying to me). At the same time it is turn-based, so not as hectic as TBOI and spelunky. You have little inventory management, as compared to Magicite. Successful runs can be very memorable and the feeling, when you beat for the first time three enemies previously thought impossible is amazing. I believe this game is truly underappreciated."
76561198042225625,Recommended,265990,33235847,Posted: 4 July,all,ikkiyakki,"The shortest tale I was told here was exactly 1 turn long: spawn with 9HP -> make a step, recieve a -9HP fireball from an unseen creature -> game over. It uses simultaneous movement system, so it's always paused for you to take your time & strategize, but there's no turning back after you hit a key. A lightning-fast strikes exchange may leave you with your jaw dropped, numb & morally destroyed after a day-long sneaky work of cave clearing, after a series of lucky duels we always tend to overestimate our fortune.It's built on Java (hence the clunky UI, push Ctrl+ for modest scaling up) & hasn't got animations, still a super-realistic dungeoneering experience, since there are lots of objects to interact with, combine & construct techniques, also it's easy to predict interaction outcomes from the common sense point. The common sense tells us that a usual guy can't stand against 3 demons in 1 room - ..and he surely dies, it tells that with a fire-ward amulet & health regeneration you can swim in lava like in water - yes, it lets you escape through a fiery river.Despite the well-known underground setting all your tactics learnt from RPG's should be abandoned at the entrance to these caves - no item hoarding allowed (traders have limited inventories), the coins are scarce (have to identify an item before selling, so no item cheaper than 20 gold is profitable), levelling up quickly is strictly not recommended (enemies spawn accordingly stronger on the new floors), in fact players try to make less actions that might give XP, etc. What really keeps me going is the chance to get LEGACIES (like in ""Rogue Legacy"") for all the future playthroughs, like bow & arrows from the start, which make early game significantly easier.I've been playing it all spring, yet *reach lvl 20* achievement stays a dream for me. Every second playthrough attempt ended in a brutal ragequit (darn java windows ain't so easy to close down), but very soon the addiction whispered to my ear: ""What if you get EXTEREMLY lucky THIS time around?"" - and I jumped back to the screen. It feels like hunting for the jackpot - you know you can win every single encounter if you have the proper set of skills & tools, but you can't develop a 100% universal hero (only 6 skills could be picked normally), so the dungeon will probably find its remedy against you sooner or later.The priceless feeling is the tension at the finger point when you stand ready to take your chance before a bunch of baddies - you are bold, you are strong & fully equipped, you are almost sure you will kick their asses.. if only fortune smiles at you a little! Or you may suddenly think to yourself: ""It's a long time there were no traps seen.."" - and make the next step to the side.. and get into a trap immidiately. Hilarious game.For rogue-like fanatics who get aroused by risk, 10/10 realistic very-careful-person simulator"
76561197997439296,Not Recommended,265990,14462352,"Posted: 14 February, 2015",all,merusalem,"tl;dr: Get one of the games listed below instead, unless you know what you do when you buy a ""real Rogue"" game - endless frustration.Positive:Compared to many other rogue-like or rogue-lite dungeon crawlers, the graphics are nice.Dying and creation of the next adventurer is fast. With each adventurer dying within 30 seconds to five minutes, this is a positive aspect.There are many extras in the game, like gaining equipment for later characters through exploration.Using other monsters to your advantage is sometimes possible.This is a true recreation of the Rogue game of 1980 with modern graphics.This game is for hardcore gamers, those who like getting their teeth pulled without anesthetics, because it is badass. :)Still, if you want to have fun playing games, I suggest to play any of these games instead - from casual to more hardcore:Claustrophobia: The Downward StruggleSword of the Stars: The PitTales of Maj'EyalDarkest DungeonWhy do I suggest these games, instead of Rogue's Tale? Any of these games will give you a feeling that you survived the last encounter (or did not) because of choices you made. In Rogue's Tale you realize each time something happens that you won or lost because of the random number generator - your decisions do not matter. Toss a coin instead - on tails you lose.It felt to me like playing an old buggy version of Rogue where the end boss can spawn one step from you when you enter the dungeon. Monsters, loot and interactable objects seem to be generated completely randomly. You do not survive or die because you made the right decisions, you do so because you had a lucky or unlucky roll. As Rogue's Tale's environment is mostly open areas (not narrow tunnels or small interconnected rooms), you can rarely use the environment to your advantage.Using other monsters to your advantage is sometimes possible. Creatures who are usually docile may attack your opponent if you lead him to them. Unfortunately some of your opponents will be of the invincible kind, so that they decimate the complete level, including you, without losing one hitpoint.This is how my playthrough for the first ten adventurers went:Some died to an invisible spike trap after a few steps.Some were slaughtered by the first brigand they encountered after a few steps.Some of them actually found weapons and armor immediately after entering the dungeon, getting them equipped just fine - and died to three opponents attacking simultaneously two minutes later.A few more tests showed a complete dependency on the game's random number generator, instead of modern game design. It is truly a recreation of the 1980ies Rogue-type games. Suffer, player! :)In my eyes, the game's major flaw is that it is Rogue. You will die because of the flip of a coin, after a few seconds or minutes."
