,Not Recommended,265990,35228490,Posted: 26 September,all,Gobab,"It has potential but much of the gameplay boils down to completely unfair RNG at times, and without a proper wiki other than some stuff the dev has on their website, you've got no clue what you're doing.Pros:-Has sounds for everything, which is nice for a roguelike because then you don't need to read the message log to know what's happened after you've been playing for a while-Interesting stuff like getting exp for lighting torches or unlocking locks or disarming traps-A cool mechanic where you can unlock free starting items for achieving things, like having one character reach level 7 means all your next characters will start with a potion of antidote-Grid inventory system in a roguelike is rare and neat-Has a 'generate a new dungeon' feature after you complete one, includes going to town mechanics to identify, buy, sell, and enchant items-Has a level editor-Dev is still patching and putting out updatesCons:-Nearly any enemy can kill you in two hits early on-Many traps can instantly kill you early on (and you can't avoid them unless you take the keen eye talent first, or spam search every step)-While confused, blinded, or feared, you can't do anything with your inventory or control your character, rendering you at the mercy of RNG when poisoned or on fire-The cool mechanic of getting free stuff through achievements is borderline required unless you have extensive knowledge of the game, which you won't have when you start-Everything in town costs so much money-You need to know everything about the game to do even half decent, the rest is up to RNGConclusion: I paid a dollar for this and if it was anything more I'd probably be pretty upset at how RNG focused it is, if it looks interesting to you, get it when it goes on sale. There's free roguelikes that does what this does better, but it has some merit to it."
